Full Integration Test
def test_full_priority_workflow():
    """
    Integration test: verifies all three functions
    work correctly together end to end.
    """
    # Arrange
    urgent_this_week = Task(title='Urgent this week',
        priority=TaskPriority.URGENT,
        due_date=datetime.now() + timedelta(days=7))  # 70pts

    high_due_today = Task(title='High due today',
        priority=TaskPriority.HIGH,
        due_date=datetime.now())  # 60pts

    overdue_blocker = Task(title='Overdue blocker',
        priority=TaskPriority.LOW,
        due_date=datetime.now() - timedelta(days=1),
        tags=['blocker'])  # 53pts

    medium_no_deadline = Task(title='Medium no deadline',
        priority=TaskPriority.MEDIUM)  # 20pts

    completed_urgent = Task(title='Completed urgent',
        priority=TaskPriority.URGENT)
    completed_urgent.mark_as_done()  # 10pts

    tasks = [overdue_blocker, completed_urgent,
             high_due_today, medium_no_deadline, urgent_this_week]

    # Act
    top_tasks = get_top_priority_tasks(tasks, limit=5)

    # Assert — verify correct order
    assert top_tasks[0].title == 'Urgent this week'   # 70
    assert top_tasks[1].title == 'High due today'     # 60
    assert top_tasks[2].title == 'Overdue blocker'    # 53
    assert top_tasks[3].title == 'Medium no deadline' # 20
    assert top_tasks[4].title == 'Completed urgent'   # 10
    assert len(top_tasks) == 5

def test_integration_empty_list():
    assert get_top_priority_tasks([], limit=5) == []

def test_integration_overdue_beats_higher_priority():
    low_overdue = Task(title='Low overdue',
        priority=TaskPriority.LOW,
        due_date=datetime.now() - timedelta(days=1))  # 45pts
    high_no_deadline = Task(title='High no deadline',
        priority=TaskPriority.HIGH)  # 40pts
    result = get_top_priority_tasks(
        [high_no_deadline, low_overdue], limit=2)
    assert result[0].title == 'Low overdue'

def test_integration_limit_respected():
    tasks = [Task(title=f'Task {i}',
             priority=TaskPriority.LOW) for i in range(10)]
    assert len(get_top_priority_tasks(tasks, limit=3)) == 3

Part 5: Reflections
What I Learned About Testing
•	Testing is about verifying outputs match expectations — not just running code
•	Test names should describe exactly what is being tested — a good name makes the test self-documenting
•	Arrange-Act-Assert pattern makes tests readable and consistent
•	Test dependencies must be respected — unit tests before integration tests
•	TDD forces you to think about behavior before writing code — catches design problems early
•	Edge cases matter as much as normal cases — capital Blocker tag silently fails without a test
•	AI helped identify behaviors I missed — REVIEW penalty, case-sensitive tags, 23-hour update quirk

TDD Key Lessons
•	RED-GREEN-REFACTOR is a discipline — always write the failing test first
•	Minimal code means just enough to pass — resist adding extra logic
•	Refactor only after tests are green — never while tests are failing
•	Each new behavior gets its own test — never test two things in one assertion

Integration Testing Key Lessons
•	Design test data deliberately — choose values that make expected scores easy to calculate
•	Test the order, not just the count — verify WHICH task is at position 0
•	Test surprising cases — overdue LOW beats on-time HIGH shows real system behavior
•	Always test empty list — every function that takes a list should handle [] gracefully

My Testing Journey
I started not knowing the difference between testing and running code. By the end I could write unit tests, integration tests, TDD tests, and bug reproduction tests — all with correct assertions and clear names.
